span.p: This step queries PRISM's web service to find all available daily data files, and then writes that list of downloadable files.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;
display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p: This step downloads the netCDF .nc files form PRISM's conversion step. This step is idempotent, and will only download files that are either missing or have updateed grid counts.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;
display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p: This step combines data from each year, while adding a time dimension. e.g. 1981-01-01_8.nc to 1981-12-31_8.nc are all merged into 1981.nc. This step is idempotent, and will not regenerate a specific year's files unless one of the dates of that year has changed.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;
display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;
display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p: This step takes the yearly files into the Zarr, and writes that to disk. Because this step only uses the yearly files and not all netCDF files like the transform_nc.py script, this functionality has to live in the separate python file which imports shared logic from transform_nc.py. This step is also idempotent, and will not act if the .nc files have not changed.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;
display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p: This step puts the zarr onto IPFS using ipldstore. Once done, it writes the CID of the HAMT root to the dataset directory, and pins it to the cluster.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;
display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p: This step pins publishes the CID to the IPNS record for the specified dataset. That way, consumers of this data only need to store and resolve IPNS records instead of keeping track of changing CIDs.
